fields.description:
When Upgrading from 4.1.2 to 4.2.0  the upgrade completed successfully but there were then two registered DNS Services. 

Before the upgrade: (from previous sos report) 
{code}
SERVICE	dns               	eucalyptus	10.196.140.15        	ENABLED 	31  	http://10.196.140.15:8773/services/Dns	arn:euca:eucalyptus::dns:10.196.140.15/
{code}
After the upgrade:
{code}
SERVICE	dns               	API_15    	API_15.dns           	ENABLED 	23  	http://10.196.140.15:8773/services/Dns	arn:euca:bootstrap:API_15:dns:API_15.dns/
SERVICE	dns               	eucalyptus	10.196.140.15_dns    	ENABLED 	23  	http://10.196.140.15:8773/services/Dns	arn:euca:bootstrap:eucalyptus:dns:10.196.140.15_dns/
{code}

It seems that not only was the Second DNS service added but the First DNS service values changed?  

In the cloud-output.log we are seeing "INFO | Registering DNS service on host 10.196.140.15" which indicates that the original service was not found at DnsUpgrades.groovy line #60.

comments.body:
[~spark] If you look at the original DNS service out put from euca-descibe-services from before the upgrade:
{code}
SERVICE	dns               	eucalyptus	10.196.140.15        	ENABLED 	31  	http://10.196.140.15:8773/services/Dns	arn:euca:eucalyptus::dns:10.196.140.15/
{code}
It is different from the output after the Upgrade:
{code} 
SERVICE	dns               	eucalyptus	10.196.140.15_dns    	ENABLED 	23  	http://10.196.140.15:8773/services/Dns	arn:euca:bootstrap:eucalyptus:dns:10.196.140.15_dns/
{code}
I was just wondering where this got changed in upgrade?
When the customer re-registers the upgraded DNS service should they deregister the other service? 
{code} 
SERVICE	dns               	eucalyptus	10.196.140.15_dns    	ENABLED 	23  	http://10.196.140.15:8773/services/Dns	arn:euca:bootstrap:eucalyptus:dns:10.196.140.15_dns/
{code}

I can't seem to reproduce this in 4.1.2 -> 4.2.0 upgrade. I had UFS/CLC co-located topology. Line #48 of DnsUpgrades.groovy should return false and does not try attempting to register again.
{noformat}
[root@g-05-06 ~]# euca-modify-property -p euca='com.eucalyptus.component.ServiceConfigurations.list(com.eucalyptus.component.id.Dns).isEmpty()'
warning: euca-modify-property is deprecated; use ``euctl'' instead
PROPERTY	euca	false was executed successfully.

{noformat}

[~spark] , [~sjones] I think we may be seeing EUCA-11624 I am seeing this in the logs:
{code}
Mon Oct 26 18:22:47 2015  WARN [StaticPropertyEntry:Eucalyptus.bootstrap:EphemeralConfiguration:arn:euca:bootstrap:Topology::external/.class java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor$Worker#5
] Failed to get property: cloud.identifier_canonicalizer because of example: [StaticDatabasePropertyEntry fieldName=com.eucalyptus.compute.common.internal.identifier.ResourceIdentifiers.ide
ntifier_canonicalizer value=null propName=cloud.identifier_canonicalizer id=null version=null creationTimestamp=null lastUpdateTimestamp=null naturalId=null]
{code}
I am not sure what the ramification of this issue would be?

It turns out that the customer was still sourcing eucarc, rather than the "new way" of:
{code}
eval `clcadmin-assume-system-credentials`
{code}
